1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,460
 Welcome to C Programming for Everybody. My name is Charles Severance and this is

2
00:00:05,460 --> 00:00:10,100
 my reading of the 1978 C Programming book written by Brian Kernigan and Dennis

3
00:00:10,100 --> 00:00:14,460
 Ritchie. At times I add my own interpretation of the material from a

4
00:00:14,460 --> 00:00:20,940
 historical perspective. Chapter 1, a tutorial introduction. Let us begin with

5
00:00:20,940 --> 00:00:25,120
 a quick introduction to C. Our aim is to show the essential elements of the

6
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:29,820
 language in real programs but without getting bogged down in details, formal

7
00:00:29,820 --> 00:00:34,940
 rules, and exceptions. At this point we are not trying to be complete or even

8
00:00:34,940 --> 00:00:39,660
 precise. We want you to get as quickly as possible to the point where you can

9
00:00:39,660 --> 00:00:44,620
 write useful programs and to do that we have to concentrate on the basics,

10
00:00:44,620 --> 00:00:49,320
 variables and constants, arithmetic, control flow, functions, and the

11
00:00:49,320 --> 00:00:54,180
 rudiments of input and output. We are quite intentionally leaving out of this

12
00:00:54,180 --> 00:00:58,500
 chapter the features of C which are of vital importance for writing bigger

13
00:00:58,500 --> 00:01:04,460
 programs. These include pointers, structures, and most of C's rich set of

14
00:01:04,460 --> 00:01:10,980
 operators, several control flow statements, and a myriad of details. This approach

15
00:01:10,980 --> 00:01:15,840
 has its drawbacks of course. Most notable is that the complete story on any

16
00:01:15,840 --> 00:01:20,980
 particular language feature is not found in a single place. The tutorial by being

17
00:01:20,980 --> 00:01:26,780
 brief may also mislead and because they cannot use the full power of C the

18
00:01:26,780 --> 00:01:31,620
 examples are not as concise and elegant as they might be. We have tried to

19
00:01:31,620 --> 00:01:36,740
 minimize these effects but be warned. Another drawback is that later chapters

20
00:01:36,740 --> 00:01:41,420
 will necessarily repeat some of this chapter. In any case experienced

21
00:01:41,420 --> 00:01:44,460
 programmers should be able to extrapolate from the material in this

22
00:01:44,460 --> 00:01:48,700
 chapter to their own programming needs. Beginners should supplement it by

23
00:01:48,700 --> 00:01:53,060
 writing small similar programs of their own. Both groups can use it as a

24
00:01:53,060 --> 00:01:57,020
 framework on which to hang the more detailed descriptions that begin in

25
00:01:57,020 --> 00:02:04,420
 chapter 2. 1.1 getting started. The only way to learn a new programming language

26
00:02:04,420 --> 00:02:09,060
 is by writing programs in it. The first program to write is the same for all

27
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:16,020
 languages. Print the words "hello world". This is the basic hurdle. To leap over it

28
00:02:16,020 --> 00:02:19,900
 you have to be able to create the program text somewhere, compile it

29
00:02:19,900 --> 00:02:26,340
 successfully, load it, run it, and find out where your output went. With these

30
00:02:26,340 --> 00:02:32,100
 mechanical details mastered everything else is comparatively easy. In

31
00:02:32,100 --> 00:02:39,180
 traditional C the program to print "hello world" is main open parenthesis

32
00:02:39,180 --> 00:02:45,140
 closed parenthesis, open curly brace, print F parenthesis double quote hello

33
00:02:45,140 --> 00:02:52,220
 comma space world backslash n double quote, closed parenthesis semicolon, closed

34
00:02:52,220 --> 00:02:57,780
 curly brace. The modern minimal version of this program needs a bit more syntax.

35
00:02:57,780 --> 00:03:05,580
 We add a single line at the beginning hashtag include space left angle

36
00:03:05,580 --> 00:03:13,300
 brackets stdio.h right angle bracket. Pound include stdio.h. We have to add

37
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:19,420
 that line for the modern program. Back to the book. Just how to run this program

38
00:03:19,420 --> 00:03:24,940
 depends on the system that you're using. As a specific example on the Unix

39
00:03:24,940 --> 00:03:29,540
 operating system you must create the source program in a file whose name ends

40
00:03:29,540 --> 00:03:37,620
 in .c such as hello.c and then you compile it with the command cc space

41
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:42,860
 hello.c. If you haven't botched anything such as omitting a character or

42
00:03:42,860 --> 00:03:47,180
 misspelling something the compilation will proceed silently and make an

43
00:03:47,180 --> 00:03:53,740
 executable file called a.out. Running that by the command a.out will

44
00:03:53,740 --> 00:03:59,700
 produce hello comma world as its output. On other systems the rules will be

45
00:03:59,700 --> 00:04:06,060
 different. Check with a local expert. On modern systems we use the gcc compiler

46
00:04:06,060 --> 00:04:14,140
 with the -ancy option to accept the legacy syntax of c. So we use gcc space

47
00:04:14,140 --> 00:04:21,940
 -ancy space hello.c and to run the resulting a.out file you usually you

48
00:04:21,940 --> 00:04:26,380
 need to prepend the local directory because most shell configurations do not

49
00:04:26,380 --> 00:04:31,140
 include the current path in the paths to search for applications so you need to

50
00:04:31,140 --> 00:04:40,260
 write ./a.out. Now for some explanations about the program itself. A c

51
00:04:40,260 --> 00:04:45,780
 program whatever its size consists of one or more functions which specify the

52
00:04:45,780 --> 00:04:51,300
 actual computing operations that are to be done. C functions are similar to

53
00:04:51,300 --> 00:04:56,860
 functions and subroutines of a Fortran program or the procedures of PL1, Pascal

54
00:04:56,860 --> 00:05:03,340
 etc. In our example main is such a function. Normally you're at liberty give

55
00:05:03,340 --> 00:05:08,100
 functions whatever names you like but main is a special name. Your program

56
00:05:08,100 --> 00:05:13,620
 begins executing at the beginning of main. This means every program must have

57
00:05:13,620 --> 00:05:18,460
 a main somewhere. Main will usually invoke other functions to perform its

58
00:05:18,460 --> 00:05:24,820
 job some coming from the same program and others from libraries of previously

59
00:05:24,820 --> 00:05:29,780
 written functions. One method of communicating data between functions is

60
00:05:29,780 --> 00:05:35,260
 by arguments. The parentheses following the function name surround the argument

61
00:05:35,260 --> 00:05:41,380
 list. Here main is a function of no arguments indicated by open parentheses

62
00:05:41,380 --> 00:05:47,100
 closed parentheses. The curly braces enclose the statements that make up the

63
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:52,900
 function. They're analogous to the do end of PL1 or the begin end of algal or

64
00:05:52,900 --> 00:05:59,660
 Pascal and so on. A function is invoked by naming it followed by a parenthesized

65
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:05,700
 list of arguments. There is no call statement as there is in Fortran or PL1.

66
00:06:05,700 --> 00:06:12,260
 The parentheses must be present even if there are no arguments. In the above

67
00:06:12,260 --> 00:06:16,060
 text the authors were making connections to the popular general purpose

68
00:06:16,060 --> 00:06:20,420
 programming languages of the time. When the book was written it was not all

69
00:06:20,420 --> 00:06:25,660
 assured that C and C like languages would ever evolve past writing high

70
00:06:25,660 --> 00:06:30,820
 performance applications like operating system kernels and device drivers. By

71
00:06:30,820 --> 00:06:35,620
 comparing C to these more general purpose languages the authors are trying

72
00:06:35,620 --> 00:06:41,420
 to plant the seed that C could have value as a general purpose language. Back

73
00:06:41,420 --> 00:06:47,860
 to the text. The line that says print F parenthesis double quote hello comma

74
00:06:47,860 --> 00:06:53,540
 space world backslash and double quote closed parentheses semicolon is a

75
00:06:53,540 --> 00:06:59,860
 function call which calls a function named print F with the argument hello

76
00:06:59,860 --> 00:07:04,660
 world. Print F is a library function which prints the output to the terminal

77
00:07:04,660 --> 00:07:09,540
 unless some other destination is specified. In this case it prints the

78
00:07:09,540 --> 00:07:15,060
 string of characters that make up its argument. Any sequence of any number of

79
00:07:15,060 --> 00:07:19,220
 characters enclosed in double quotes is called a character string or string

80
00:07:19,220 --> 00:07:24,460
 constant. For the moment our only use of the character strings will be as

81
00:07:24,460 --> 00:07:31,260
 arguments to print F and other functions. The sequence backslash n in the string

82
00:07:31,260 --> 00:07:36,820
 is C notation for the new line character which when printed advances the terminal

83
00:07:36,820 --> 00:07:42,340
 to the left margin on the next line. If you leave out the backslash n, a

84
00:07:42,340 --> 00:07:46,940
 worthwhile experiment by the way, you'll find that your output is not terminated

85
00:07:46,940 --> 00:07:51,100
 by a line feed. The only way to get a new line character into the print F's

86
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:58,020
 argument is with backslash n. If you try to break it into two lines like print

87
00:07:58,020 --> 00:08:05,740
 F quote hello world and then just hit the return double quote close parenthesis

88
00:08:05,740 --> 00:08:10,700
 semicolon on a new line the C compiler will print out unfriendly diagnostics

89
00:08:10,700 --> 00:08:15,780
 about missing quotes. Print F never supplies a new line automatically so

90
00:08:15,780 --> 00:08:21,060
 multiple calls can be used to build up an output line in stages. Our first

91
00:08:21,060 --> 00:08:25,860
 program could have just as well been written as main open parenthesis close

92
00:08:25,860 --> 00:08:33,660
 parenthesis open curly brace print F quote hello quote semicolon print F

93
00:08:33,660 --> 00:08:41,340
 quote world quote semicolon print F backslash n semicolon and then on a sixth

94
00:08:41,340 --> 00:08:46,620
 line close curly brace and it would have produced the identical output. Note that

95
00:08:46,620 --> 00:08:51,620
 backslash n represents only a single character an escape sequence like

96
00:08:51,620 --> 00:08:56,700
 backslash n provides a general and extensible mechanism for representing

97
00:08:56,700 --> 00:09:01,940
 hard-to-get or invisible characters. Among the others that C provides are

98
00:09:01,940 --> 00:09:07,540
 backslash T for tab backslash B for backspace backslash double quote for

99
00:09:07,540 --> 00:09:15,660
 double quote and backslash backslash for the backslash itself. 1.2 page 8

100
00:09:15,660 --> 00:09:20,780
 variables and arithmetic. The next program prints the following table of

101
00:09:20,780 --> 00:09:25,100
 Fahrenheit temperatures in their centigrade or Celsius equivalence. Using

102
00:09:25,100 --> 00:09:33,260
 the formula C equals parenthesis 5 divided by 9 close parenthesis parenthesis F - 32.

103
00:09:33,260 --> 00:09:39,860
 The table contains Fahrenheit of 0 Celsius of negative 17.8 Fahrenheit of

104
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:47,620
 20 Celsius of negative 6.7 Fahrenheit of 40 Celsius of 4.4 and so forth. Here is

105
00:09:47,620 --> 00:09:54,460
 the program itself. For reference this program is on page 29 of the textbook.

106
00:09:54,460 --> 00:10:01,220
 So it starts with #include stdio.h to include the standard

107
00:10:01,220 --> 00:10:06,140
 library then it has a comment that says print the Fahrenheit Celsius table for F

108
00:10:06,140 --> 00:10:14,500
 equals 0 comma 20 comma dot dot dot comma 300 close common main open

109
00:10:14,500 --> 00:10:21,900
 parenthesis close parenthesis open curly brace int lower comma upper comma step

110
00:10:21,900 --> 00:10:30,980
 semicolon float far comma Celsius lower equals zero semicolon followed by a

111
00:10:30,980 --> 00:10:37,820
 comment upper equals 300 semicolon followed by a comment step equals 20

112
00:10:37,820 --> 00:10:46,060
 semicolon followed by a comment far equals lower and then while open

113
00:10:46,060 --> 00:10:52,700
 parenthesis far less than or equal to upper close parenthesis open curly brace Celsius

114
00:10:52,700 --> 00:11:02,420
 equals parenthesis 5.0 slash 9.0 close parenthesis asterisk open parenthesis far

115
00:11:02,420 --> 00:11:12,540
 minus 32.0 close parenthesis semicolon. Then a printf statement printf open

116
00:11:12,540 --> 00:11:22,660
 parenthesis double quote percent 4.0 f space percent 6.1 f backslash n close

117
00:11:22,660 --> 00:11:31,900
 quote comma far comma Celsius close parenthesis semicolon. Far equals far

118
00:11:31,900 --> 00:11:38,340
 plus step and then a closing curly brace to finish the while statement and then a

119
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:44,660
 closing curly brace to finish the main statement. The first two lines slash

120
00:11:44,660 --> 00:11:51,940
 star print Fahrenheit to Celsius table for F equals 0 comma 20 dot dot dot 300

121
00:11:51,940 --> 00:11:58,100
 star slash are a comment which in this case explains briefly what the program

122
00:11:58,100 --> 00:12:03,260
 does. Any characters between slash star and star slash are ignored by the

123
00:12:03,260 --> 00:12:08,660
 compiler. They may be used to freely make the program easier to understand.

124
00:12:08,660 --> 00:12:15,860
 Comments may appear anywhere a blank or new line can. In C all variables must be

125
00:12:15,860 --> 00:12:20,660
 declared before use usually at the beginning of a function before any

126
00:12:20,660 --> 00:12:25,420
 executable statements. If you forget a declaration you will get a diagnostic

127
00:12:25,420 --> 00:12:31,140
 from the compiler. A declaration consider consists of a type and a list

128
00:12:31,140 --> 00:12:36,820
 of variables that have that type as in int lower comma upper comma step

129
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:45,220
 semicolon float far comma Celsius semicolon. The type int implies that the

130
00:12:45,220 --> 00:12:50,740
 variables listed are integers. Float stands for floating point i.e. numbers

131
00:12:50,740 --> 00:12:55,900
 which may have a fractional part. Precision of both int and float depends

132
00:12:55,900 --> 00:13:00,900
 on the particular machine that you are using. On the PDP 11 for instance an

133
00:13:00,900 --> 00:13:08,840
 int is a 16-bit signed number. That is one that lies between negative 32,768

134
00:13:08,840 --> 00:13:16,380
 and positive 32,767. A float number is a 32-bit quantity which

135
00:13:16,380 --> 00:13:21,260
 amounts to about seven significant digits with a magnitude of about 10 to

136
00:13:21,260 --> 00:13:31,700
 minus 38 and 10 plus 38. Chapter 2 lists the sizes for other machines. I would

137
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:35,900
 note that the 1970s was a time of transition in the amount of memory

138
00:13:35,900 --> 00:13:41,860
 installed in computers. The C language int type was 16 bits in the older but

139
00:13:41,860 --> 00:13:46,840
 more generally available computers like the PDP 11. C could be used to write

140
00:13:46,840 --> 00:13:51,420
 programs like the UNIX operating system that made efficient use of available

141
00:13:51,420 --> 00:13:58,140
 memory. In particular the 1978 version of C did not require that computers support

142
00:13:58,140 --> 00:14:04,900
 32-bit integers. But 32,768 is a pretty small number. The size of an

143
00:14:04,900 --> 00:14:09,860
 integer affected the maximum size of arrays and strings. A lot of early C

144
00:14:09,860 --> 00:14:14,580
 programs used the long type to get at least a 32-bit integer capable of

145
00:14:14,580 --> 00:14:20,340
 representing numbers up to about 2 billion. In modern computers and

146
00:14:20,340 --> 00:14:25,940
 databases we tend to choose between 32-bit and 64-bit integers. Back to the

147
00:14:25,940 --> 00:14:32,460
 text. C provides several other basic data types besides int and float. Char is

148
00:14:32,460 --> 00:14:39,100
 a character, a single byte. Short is a short integer. Long is a long integer and

149
00:14:39,100 --> 00:14:44,820
 double is a double precision floating point. The size of these objects are also

150
00:14:44,820 --> 00:14:49,500
 machine dependent and details are in chapter 2. There are also arrays,

151
00:14:49,500 --> 00:14:54,180
 structures, and unions of these basic types and pointers to them and functions

152
00:14:54,180 --> 00:14:59,660
 that return them, all of which we will meet in due course. The actual

153
00:14:59,660 --> 00:15:02,940
 computation in our temperature conversion program begins with the

154
00:15:02,940 --> 00:15:10,140
 assignments lower equals zero, upper equals 300, step equals 20, far equals

155
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:15,660
 lower, all ending with semicolon. These set the variables to their starting

156
00:15:15,660 --> 00:15:22,260
 values. Individual statements are terminated by semicolons. Each line of

157
00:15:22,260 --> 00:15:27,340
 the table is computed in the same way so we use a loop which repeats once per

158
00:15:27,340 --> 00:15:33,460
 line. This is the purpose of the while statement. While parentheses far less

159
00:15:33,460 --> 00:15:38,140
 than or equal upper closed parentheses open curly brace, then the body of the

160
00:15:38,140 --> 00:15:43,940
 loop, and then closed curly brace. The condition in the parentheses is tested.

161
00:15:43,940 --> 00:15:49,420
 If it is true, i.e. far is less than or equal to upper, the body of the loop, all

162
00:15:49,420 --> 00:15:53,420
 of the statements included between the open curly brace and the closed curly

163
00:15:53,420 --> 00:15:59,140
 brace are executed. Then the condition is retested. If true, the body is executed

164
00:15:59,140 --> 00:16:06,060
 again. When the test becomes false, i.e. far exceeds upper, the loop ends and

165
00:16:06,060 --> 00:16:10,300
 execution continues at the statement that follows the loop. There are no

166
00:16:10,300 --> 00:16:15,860
 further statements in the program so it terminates. The body of a while loop can

167
00:16:15,860 --> 00:16:21,380
 be one or more statements enclosed in braces as the temperature converter or a

168
00:16:21,380 --> 00:16:27,100
 single statement without braces as in while open parentheses i less than j

169
00:16:27,100 --> 00:16:34,300
 closed parentheses, i equals 2 times i semicolon. In either case, the statements

170
00:16:34,300 --> 00:16:39,540
 controlled by the while are indented by one tab stop so you can see at a glance

171
00:16:39,540 --> 00:16:45,420
 what statements are inside the loop. The indentation emphasizes the logical

172
00:16:45,420 --> 00:16:49,820
 structure of the program. Although C is quite permissive about statement

173
00:16:49,820 --> 00:16:55,020
 positioning, proper indentation and the use of whitespace are critical in making

174
00:16:55,020 --> 00:17:00,300
 programs easy for people to read. We recommend writing only one statement per

175
00:17:00,300 --> 00:17:05,700
 line and usually leaving blanks around operators. The position of the braces is

176
00:17:05,700 --> 00:17:11,420
 less important. We have chosen one of the several popular styles. Pick a style

177
00:17:11,420 --> 00:17:17,580
 that suits you and then use it consistently. I would add that with these

178
00:17:17,580 --> 00:17:23,260
 words the authors triggered a great debate about how to best indent code

179
00:17:23,260 --> 00:17:28,740
 and use curly braces that continues to this day. The indentation style used in

180
00:17:28,740 --> 00:17:34,540
 this book is often referred to as the KNR style. It tends to put open braces at

181
00:17:34,540 --> 00:17:38,900
 the end of statements like if and while to keep code more compact in terms of

182
00:17:38,900 --> 00:17:44,420
 the number of lines of code. The best advice is not to debate at all. When you

183
00:17:44,420 --> 00:17:49,220
 modify someone else's code just imitate the style that they used when they wrote

184
00:17:49,220 --> 00:17:57,780
 their code. Back to the text. Most of the work it's done in the body of the loop.

185
00:17:57,780 --> 00:18:02,620
 The Celsius temperature is computed and assigned to the Celsius variable by the

186
00:18:02,620 --> 00:18:11,060
 statement Celsius equals open parentheses 5.0 slash 9.0 close parentheses, asterisk

187
00:18:11,060 --> 00:18:18,660
 open parentheses, far minus 32.0 close parentheses, semicolon. The reason for

188
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:25,220
 using 5.0 slash 9.0 instead of the simpler looking 5 slash 9 is that in C

189
00:18:25,220 --> 00:18:31,140
 as in many other languages integer division truncates so that any fractional

190
00:18:31,140 --> 00:18:38,780
 part is discarded. Thus 5 slash 9 is 0 and of course so would then all the

191
00:18:38,780 --> 00:18:44,000
 temperatures be 0. A decimal point in a constant indicates that it is floating

192
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:53,900
 point so that 5.0 over 9.0 is 0.555 repeating which is what we want. We also

193
00:18:53,900 --> 00:19:00,780
 wrote 32.0 instead of 32 even though since far is afloat 32 would

194
00:19:00,780 --> 00:19:05,420
 automatically be converted to float before the subtraction. But as a matter

195
00:19:05,420 --> 00:19:08,900
 of style it's wise to write floating-point constants with explicit

196
00:19:08,900 --> 00:19:13,580
 decimal points even when they have integral values. It emphasizes their

197
00:19:13,580 --> 00:19:18,020
 floating-point nature for human readers and ensures the compiler will see things

198
00:19:18,020 --> 00:19:23,940
 the way you do as well. I would note that for those of you familiar with Python

199
00:19:23,940 --> 00:19:30,620
 before Python 3 integer division truncated and returned an integer just

200
00:19:30,620 --> 00:19:36,500
 like C. In Python 3 one of the major improvements was that the division of

201
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:41,340
 two integers performed the division operation in floating-point and returns

202
00:19:41,340 --> 00:19:48,220
 a floating-point result. C and Python 2 made the choice because of efficiency.

203
00:19:48,220 --> 00:19:52,820
 Integer division with truncation especially for 16-bit numbers was quite

204
00:19:52,820 --> 00:19:57,580
 fast in the 1970s computers compared to floating-point division that kept the

205
00:19:57,580 --> 00:20:03,180
 fractional part intact. Early PDP 11 computers did integer division in

206
00:20:03,180 --> 00:20:07,980
 hardware while all floating-point was done with loops and functions so it was

207
00:20:07,980 --> 00:20:13,740
 far slower. If you wanted to write fast code in 1970s you avoided floating-point

208
00:20:13,740 --> 00:20:20,700
 numbers except for special situations. Modern computers usually do 64-bit

209
00:20:20,700 --> 00:20:25,860
 floating-point operations almost at the same speed as integer division so we

210
00:20:25,860 --> 00:20:29,700
 don't need to allow programmers to avoid using floating-point computations in

211
00:20:29,700 --> 00:20:34,860
 their code. The detailed rules for when integers are converted to floating-point

212
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:41,540
 are in chapter 2. For now notice that the assignment far equals lower semicolon

213
00:20:41,540 --> 00:20:48,600
 and the test while far less than or equals upper both work as expected. The

214
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:54,780
 int is converted to a float before the operation is done. This example also

215
00:20:54,780 --> 00:21:00,420
 shows a bit more of how printf works. printf is actually a general purpose

216
00:21:00,420 --> 00:21:06,020
 format conversion function which we will describe completely in chapter 7. Its

217
00:21:06,020 --> 00:21:11,300
 first argument is a string of characters to be printed with each percent sign

218
00:21:11,300 --> 00:21:16,620
 indicating where one of the other second third etc arguments is to be

219
